            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Rostami-Jones is a product of two distinct intellectual traditions. His father, an Iranian immigrant and history professor, and his mother, a Midwestern librarian with a love for cataloging, raised him in a Berkeley home where books were structural elements and dinner conversations were Socratic dialogues. The hyphen in his name was a deliberate choice by his parents, a bridge between cultures he has spent his life navigating.\n\nHis educational journey was one of passion, not pragmatism. While his peers in the early 90s were flocking to computer science, Kai pursued a degree in East Asian Studies at UC Santa Cruz, captivated by the elegant simplicity of Japanese aesthetics and organization. Graduating into the teeth of the first dot-com boom, he felt adrift. He took a temp job organizing content for a fledgling web directory, a role he initially dismissed as clerical. This, however, was his turning point. He realized the chaotic digital frontier desperately needed the very principles of structure, hierarchy, and clarity he had studied. He had found his calling: Information Architecture.\n\nNow, at 48, Kai is a veteran of San Francisco\u2019s tech cycles. He has survived the bust, the rise of mobile, and the current AI craze, remaining a stable, thoughtful presence in a field defined by frantic change. He lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood he loves for its fog-laced quiet and proximity to Golden Gate Park. His 2.8-mile Muni commute to his SoMa office is a cherished ritual, a time for reading paperbacks and observing the city, not staring at a screen.\n\nHis social life is small but deep, centered on a few friends from different eras of his life. Conversations over craft beer in a dimly lit bar are his preferred form of connection. Kai has no desire to become a VP or found a startup. His dream is to take a sabbatical to write a book exploring the connections between ancient library systems and user-friendly digital design. He loves San Francisco not for its disruptive energy, but for its layers\u2014the history, the resilience, the quiet corners. He sees his role not as a builder of the new, but as a curator of the humane within it."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being ten, cross-legged on the Persian rug in their Berkeley living room. His mother was showing him how to apply catalog labels to a stack of his father\u2019s new history books. The smell of old paper and his mother\u2019s quiet focus mixed with his father\u2019s voice from his study, explaining a point about the Safavid dynasty. It wasn\u2019t just about organizing books; it was about honoring knowledge. In that moment, he learned that structure was a form of love, a lesson that became the foundation of his entire career.\n\n2.\nIt was 1996, in a drab cubicle at a web startup he secretly disdained. He stared at a raw list of thousands of uncategorized URLs, a digital mess that felt like pure chaos. As he despaired, a memory of a Japanese rock garden from a textbook surfaced\u2014its careful, deliberate placement. Suddenly, the chaos wasn't daunting; it was an opportunity. He saw the structure waiting to be revealed. That day, adrift in the dot-com sea, he found his shore. He wasn't just a temp; he was an architect.\n\n3.\nHe remembers the eerie silence of the office in 2001 after the third round of layoffs. He was helping his friend pack a cardboard box, the ping-pong table collecting dust in the corner. The bravado had vanished, replaced by a hollow feeling. Kai survived that bust not by being the flashiest, but by being the most organized. It cemented in him a deep distrust of hype and a quiet commitment to building things that last, not just things that grow fast. Resilience, he realized, was quieter than disruption.\n\n4.\nOne foggy Tuesday evening in his early thirties, he stepped off the 5-Fulton and walked into Golden Gate Park instead of going home. The fog was so thick it muted the city, swallowing the tops of the cypress trees. He felt the damp air on his face and smelled the eucalyptus. It wasn't lonely; it was profoundly peaceful. This was his San Francisco\u2014not the frantic hub, but a layered city that offered stillness. He felt truly, deeply at home in that moment of gentle obscurity.\n\n5.\nHe thinks of a night two winters ago at The Plough and the Stars, the condensation fogging the windows. He and an old friend were arguing good-naturedly over the merits of a new biography, their pints of porter nearly empty. There was no talk of valuations or user acquisition, only ideas and shared history. The warmth of the pub and the easy flow of conversation felt more valuable than any stock option. It crystallized his definition of a rich life: a small table, a good friend, and a conversation with depth."
